<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900419-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>900419-0015.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>04/19/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   EASTERN AIRLINES was turned over to a trustee by abankruptcy judge, who took control of the financiallybattered carrier away from Texas Air and Chairman FrankLorenzo. Named as trustee was Martin R. Shugrue, who wasousted last year as president of Continental Airlines, TexasAir's other airline unit. Unsecured creditors sought atrustee because they blamed management for Eastern'sever-growing losses.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Treasury bonds sank for the second day in a row, sendingstock prices and the dollar lower. The benchmark 30-yearTreasury issue fell 1 1/8 points, pushing the yield up to8.83%, the highest in nearly a year. The Dow Jonesindustrials slid 32.89, to 2732.88.                                                                                                          Oil prices skidded as much as 70 cents a barrel on worldmarkets, reflecting disappointment that a meeting of threekey OPEC members failed to result in any action.   ---   The U.S. trade deficit shrank sharply in February, to$6.49 billion, the smallest gap in over six years. Importsslid 7.6%, led by a plunge in oil buying. Analysts said theimprovement reflected the weak economy.   ---   Brazil plans to resume negotiations on its $115 billionforeign debt and to begin efforts to sell off statecompanies. The actions reflect the government's belief thatits new anti-inflation program is working.   ---   ATandamp;T's profit rose 12% in the first quarter, buoyed bycontinued strength in its long-distance business and slimmercosts. Still, earnings were slightly below expectations.   ---   USX may not get anywhere near the $1.5 billion it hoped toraise by selling oil and gas properties. Such a developmentcould fuel Carl Icahn's campaign against USX management.   ---   Ford is negotiating to buy the auto finance operations ofMarine Midland Banks, which in the 1980s led an unsuccessfulrush by commercial banks into the car-loan business.   ---   Dayton Hudson is said to be the front-runner to acquireMarshall Field's. The department-store chain is being sold byB.A.T to help fend off a takeover by Sir James Goldsmith.   ---   A bill to help discount retailers sue competitors andmanufacturers that conspire to fix prices was approved by theHouse. The legislation has prompted a Bush veto threat.   ---   Kidder Peabody isn't liable for damages in an allegedinsider-trading case relating to Maxus Energy's 1983 takeoverof Natomas, a judge ruled. The case involved Martin Siegel,who worked for Kidder, and Ivan Boesky.   ---   Apple Computer's profit jumped 134% in the quarter due toimproved profit margins, brisk new-product sales and strongforeign sales.   ---   Merrill Lynch's profit rose 11% in the first quarter,while Shearson had a $915 million loss. Both were hurt by theslump in investment banking.   ---   Coca-Cola's earnings climbed 9.1% in the first quarter,fueled by a strong 9% growth in international volume for itssoft-drink products.   ---   A fiscal 1991 budget plan was unveiled by House BudgetChairman Panetta, but Democrats were divided over cuts inmilitary spending.   ---   G. Heileman Brewing is negotiating to restructure its hugebank debt, the result of its $1.3 billion buy-out in 1987 byAustralian Alan Bond.   ---   Occidental Petroleum's profit surged 61% in the quarter,boosted by oil and natural-gas operations.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 147,130,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2732.88, off 32.89; transportation 1172.12, off 13.51;utilities 211.96, off 1.76.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3260.36, off36.15.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.19, off 0.57;spot index 135.31, off 0.10.   Dollar: 158.10 yen, off 1.58; 1.6722 marks, off 0.0046.</TEXT></DOC>